cp||fp||at|^B@2^Y@3P|FP||AT|laying defensively before the Dummy is no more difficult than playing before the Declarer, for you see not only your own cards but those in the Dummy. Nine times out of ten the Dummy's holding in the led suit will furnish the clue for Second Hand's proper play. Against no-trump contracts, particularly, it is no great problem for Second Hand to find the correct defense.|
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


AT|

There is an old Whist maxim that Second Hand should play low  - |cp|8|at|"Second Hand low"|cp||at| - which is analogous to that other one already discussed (|cp|8|at|"Third Hand high"|cp||at|). This saying has a lot of truth in it, in spite of the fact that it was at one time much overdone in the observance. The formula is still good, but it must be phrased somewhat differently, as follows: ^*IPlay low Second Hand unless there is some good reason for doing otherwise.^*N|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


AT|

The most obvious situation for playing Second Hand low occurs when the play of a high card will certainly sacrifice a trick. The following distribution illustrates the point.|
