^-{    Summary    }
^-|CS||cp||fp||at|^B@2^z@3D|FP||AT|efensive play by Second Hand means playing|cp|8|at| "Second Hand low" |cp||at|sometimes and |cp|8|at|"covering an honor with an honor" |cp||at|other times. Such rules as can be formulated are as follows:|
PG| ***** 158 ***** |


AT|

^*B When playing Second Hand before the Dummy - ^*N
@D Play low when to play high will certainly sacrifice a trick.  
@D Try to capture an adverse honor whenever you play to win a trick.
@d Play low when you make the Declarer guess on a double finesse from Dummy.
@d With a sequence, play high to make sure of 1 trick (if Dummy has a threatening card).
@d With a sequence, play low when to do so may make Declarer consider safety first. 
@d When Dummy has no high cards, use common sense.
@d With the King and the nine ^*Ior^*N Ten, cover Declarer's Queen lead.
@d Cover Declarer's Jack lead with the Queen whenever Dummy holds two threatening cards.
@d Do not cover Declarer's Jack lead with the Queen when Dummy holds only one threatening card. 
@d Cover Declarer's Jack lead with the Queen whenever not to do so will place you under Dummy's subsequent tenace.
@d Cover Declarer's Jack, or even Ten, to try to establish a tenace over Dummy in Partner's hand.
@d Cover Declarer's Jack or Ten with even the King when Dummy holds two honors, and you foresee that not to cover may place you in a tenace position under Dummy.
@d Do not cover when your King must win the third round anyway.|
PG| ***** 159 ***** |


AT|

^*BWhen playing Second Hand before the Declarer^*N - 
@D Always cover a bare honor led from Dummy (except when you hold a great many cards of the led suit).
@d Do not cover when an honor is led from a sequence in the Dummy (except when your honor heads a doubleton). |
